{{!-- ********************* CREATE CONVERSATIONS ********************* --}}

  <div id="createConversation" class="row">
  <div class="col-sm-12">
    <h3 ><a href="#createConversation"># Create conversation</a></h3>  
  </div>

  <div class="col-sm-5">
    <h5 class="HeadingH HeadingH--dark">DEFAULTS</h5>
    <p> If you haven't created a conversation in the app yet, try it out! Just like in the app, the fields are optional and there are defaults. The API key is the only required data field.
<pre><code data-language="javascript">short_url: false 
topic: ""
description: ""
</code></pre>
    <p> Passing <code>short_url: true</code> will return an easily typeable shortlink: <pre> <code data-language="javascript"> pol.is/b2xpm7w </code> </pre> 
    <p>Some conversations are more sensitive and require security. There are two tiers: </p>
    <h5 class="HeadingH HeadingH--dark"> LONG LINKS </h5> <p> <code>short_url: false</code> assumes your users can be trusted not to share a single link to the conversation. This is similar to YouTube & Google Docs, which use very long strings of letters and numbers to ensure that no one without the link can find the location of the document or the video on the internet. Good for internal business communication - easy to share, low overhead, secure enough.</p>

    <h5 class="HeadingH HeadingH--dark"> SINGLE USE URLs </h5> <p> Assumes that users will not be trusted to keep a link secret - renders each link useless once it is used. See <a href="#addingUsers">Creating single use URLs</a>.</p>

      <p style="color: #c0392b;"><i class="fa fa-bell"></i><strong> Heads up! </strong> </p> <div style="border-left: 3px solid #c0392b; padding-left: 10px"> <p style="display: inline"> Even if you plan on generating single-use urls, we still return a reusable url from this call: the response to create a conversation <em> always </em> returns a valid url. Passing the default</p> <code>short_url: false</code> <p style="display:inline"> makes this more secure. An example of when you might want this? Ask a bunch of customers a question by sending them single use urls, then use the long link to share the results with your coworkers internally. </p> </div>

  </div>
  <div class="col-sm-7">

<h5 class="HeadingF HeadingF--light"> REQUEST </h5>
<pre>
<code class="code_sample code_curl" data-language="shell">curl -X POST -s "https://pol.is/api/v3/conversations" \
      --user POLIS_API_KEY: \
      -F topic="Should we raise the minimum wage?" \
      -F description="It's currently under $10/hr, What do you think?" \
      -F short_url=true \
      -F strict_moderation=false 
</code>
<code class="code_sample code_ruby" style="display:none;" data-language="ruby">#NOTE this expects that you have done something like 'export POLIS_API_KEY=your_polis_api_key' in your environment before starting your ruby process. We recommend that you avoid putting your API key directly into your source code.

require 'net/http'
require 'uri'
require 'json'

uri = URI.parse('https://pol.is/api/v3/conversations')

http = Net::HTTP.new(uri.host, uri.port)
http.use_ssl = true

request = Net::HTTP::Post.new(uri.path, {
    'Content-Type' =>'application/json'
})
request.basic_auth ENV['POLIS_API_KEY'], ''

data = {
    'topic' => "Should we raise the minimum wage?",
    'description' => "It's currently under $10/hr, What do you think?",
    'short_url' => false,
    'strict_moderation' => false,
}

request.body = data.to_json
response = http.request(request)

puts response.body
</code>
</pre>
  <h5 class="HeadingF HeadingF--light">RESPONSE</h5>
<pre> <code data-language="javascript">{
  conversation_id: "1234abc",
  url: "pol.is/1234abc",
}
</code></pre>

